ril 3, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"2 Times\"<ref name=\"2 times\">{{cite web |title=New Music: Famous Dex feat. Wiz Khalifa & Rich the Kid \u2013 '2 Times (Remix)' |url=http://www.rap-up.com/2016/06/22/new-music-famous-dex-wiz-khalifa-rich-the-kid-2-times/ |website=Rap-Up |accessdate=February 27, 2018}}</ref>\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 2015\n| \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014\n|\n| ''Dexter's Laboratory''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Drip from My Walk\"<ref name=\"drip from my walk\">{{cite web |last1=Weinstein |first1=Max |title=Famous Dex Drops 'Drip From My Walk' Remix With Lil Yachty \u2013 XXL |url=http://www.xxlmag.com/news/2016/11/famous-dex-lil-yachty-drip-from-my-walk-remix/ |website=XXL Mag |accessdate=February 27, 2018}}</ref>\n| \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014\n|\n| ''Drippy''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"[[Pick It Up (Famous Dex song)|Pick It Up]]\"<ref name=\"Billboard\" /><br/><small>(featuring [[ASAP Rocky|A$AP Rocky]])</small>\n| 2017\n| 54 || 26 || 60\n|\n* [[Recording Industry Association of America|RIAA]]: 2\u00d7 Platinum<ref name=\"RIAA\">{{cite web|url=https://www.riaa.com/gold-platinum/?tab_active=default-award&se=famous+dex#search_section|title=Gold & Platinum - RIAA|publisher=[[Recording Industry Association of America]]|accessdate=March 17, 2018}}</ref>\n| ''[[Dex Meets Dexter]]''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"In the Bank\"<br/><small>(featuring [[YoungBoy Never Broke Again]])</small>\n| rowspan=\"4\"| 2018\n| \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014\n|\n|{{N/A|Non-album single}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"[[Japan (Famous Dex song)|Japan]]\"<ref name=\"broadway world\" /> \n| 28 || 18 || 40\n|\n* [[Recording Industry Association of America|RIAA]]: Platinum<ref name=\"RIAA\"/>\n\n| rowspan=\"2\"| ''Dex Meets Dexter''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Light\"<br/><small>(featuring [[Drax Project]])</small><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.broadwayworld.com/bwwmusic/article/Famous-Dex-Drax-Project-Join-Forces-for-New-Single-LIGHT-Out-Now-20180330|title=Famous Dex & Drax Project Join Forces for New Single LIGHT Out Now|first=TV News|last=Desk|website=BroadwayWorld.com|accessdate=November 3, 2019}}</ref>\n| \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Nervous\"<br/><small>(featuring [[Lil Baby]], [[Rich The Kid]] & Jay Critch)</small>\n| \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014\n|\n|rowspan=\"3\" {{N/A|Non-album singles}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Fully Loaded\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://allhiphop.com/music/famous-dex-fully-loaded-ft-lil-gotit-4m-9S-Ocx0arOHzzB6pKqw/|title=Famous Dex - \"Fully Loaded \" Ft. Lil Gotit|website=AllHipHop.com|language=en|access-date=2019-05-28}}</ref><br/><small>(featuring Lil Gotit)</small>\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 2019\n|| \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"[[Proofread (Famous Dex song)|Proofread]]\"<br/><small>(featuring [[Wiz Khalifa]])</small>\n| \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014\n|\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| \"What I Like\"<br/><small>(featuring [[Tyga]] & [[Rich the Kid|Rich The Kid]])</small>\n| 2020 || \u2014 || \u2014\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|}\n\n===Guest appearances===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|+ List of non-single guest appearances, with other performing artists, showing year released and album name\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:18em;\"| Title\n! scope=\"col\" | Year\n! scope=\"col\" | Other artist(s)\n! scope=\"col\" | Album\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | \"Rari\"\n| rowspan=\"4\" | 2016\n| [[Carnage (DJ)|Carnage]], [[Lil Yachty]], [[Ugly God]]\n| {{N/A}}\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | \"Honor Roll\"\n| DJ Twin, [[Lil Yachty]], [[Sean Kingston]]\n| ''Day 1 EP''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | \"Straight Up\"\n| Rich The Kid, [[Playboi Carti]]\n| rowspan=\"2\" |''[[Keep Flexin]]''\n| rowspan=\"2\" |''[[Keep Flexin]]''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | \"Coach Cartier\"\n|[[ASAP Ferg]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | \"Mattress\" (Remix)\n| rowspan=\"13\" |2017\n| ASAP Ferg, [[ASAP Rocky]], [[Playboi Carti]], [[Rich the Kid]]\n|''[[Still Striving]]''\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | \"DiegoDexterDuke\"\n| Diego Money, YSL Duke\n| rowspan=\"3\" | ''Diego & Friends''\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | \"Hop Out\"\n| Diego Money\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | \"New Rage\"\n| Diego Money, Xavier Wulf, Warhol.SS\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | \"Made In China\" \n| [[Higher Brothers]]\n| ''Black Cab''\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | \"Pull Up\"\n| [[Jay Critch]]\n| {{N/A}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | \"Digital\" \n| [[Lil Tracy]]\n| ''XOXO''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | \"Gotcho Bitch\"\n| Lil Wop\n| ''Wake-N-Bake''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | \"Cautious\"\n| Rocket Da Goon, [[Maxo Kream]]\n| ''Pluto Talk''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | \"Blade of Woe\"\n| [[Trippie Redd]]\n| ''[[A Love Letter to You]]''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | \"Things I Brought\"\n| UnoTheActivist\n| ''Live.Shyne.Die''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | \"Zeta Zero 0.5\" \n| [[6IX9INE]], Dalyb, Schlosser\n| {{N/A}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | \"Like a Glock\"\n| Lil Tracy \n| ''Tracy's Manga''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | \"ILYSM\"\n| 2018\n| [[Robb Banks]]\n| ''[[Molly World]]''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | \"F**k This Place Up\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://music.apple.com/us/artist/hayes/1453590470|title=\u200eHayes on Apple Music|website=Apple Music|language=en-us|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n|2020\n|Hayes\n|{{N/a}}\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{official|https://dexterofficial.com/}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dex, Famous}}\n[[Category:Rappers from Chicago]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1993 births]]\n[[Category:African-American male rappers]]\n[[Category:Midwest hip hop musicians]]\n__NOTOC__\n", "name_user": "80.233.57.241", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Famous_Dex"}
{"title_page": "M\u00e1ire Rua O'Brien", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| honorific_prefix   = \n| name               = M\u00e1ire Rua O'Brien\n| honorific_suffix   = \n| image              = M\u00e1ire Rua O'Brien.jpg\n| image_size         = \n| alt                = \n| caption            = \n| native_name        = \n| native_name_lang   = \n| birth_name         = M\u00e1ire Rua MacMahon\n| birth_date         = 1615/1616\n| birth_place        = [[Clonderalaw]], County Clare, Ireland\n| death_date         = 1686 (aged 70/71)\n| death_place        = \n| resting_place      = \n| residence          = \n| nationality        = Irish\n| citizenship        = \n| known_for          = \n| notable_works      = \n| parents            = \n| relatives          = \n| signature          = \n}}\n\n'''M\u00e1ire Rua O'Brien''' (1615/1616 \u2013 1686) was an Irish aristocrat, and notorious figure in Irish legend for her violent and murderous actions. <ref name=Murphy>{{cite book|last1=Murphy|first1=Maureen|editor1-last=McGuire|editor1-first=James|editor2-last=Quinn|editor2-first=James|title=[[Dictionary of Irish Biography]]|date=2009|publisher=Cambridge University Press|location=Cambridge|chapter=O'Brien, M\u00e1ire (\u2018M\u00e1ire Rua\u2019)}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nM\u00e1ire Rua O'Brien was born in 1615 or 1616.<ref name=\"Clare Library\">{{cite web |title=Clare People: Maire Rua |url=http://www.clarelibrary.ie/eolas/coclare/people/ruadh.htm |website=www.clarelibrary.ie |accessdate=2 April 2020}}</ref> She was known as M\u00e1ire Rua or Red Mary due to her red hair.<ref name=\"Aesthete\">{{cite web |title=The Legacy of M\u00e1ire R\u00faa |url=https://theirishaesthete.com/2016/10/19/the-legacy-of-maire-rua/ |website=The Irish Aesthete |accessdate=2 April 2020 |date=19 October 2016}}</ref> She was the daughter of lord of East Corcabaskin or [[Clonderalaw]], Sir Torlach Rua MacMahon and the youngest daughter of [[Connor O'Brien, 3rd Earl of Thomond]], Mary. Some sources have her place of birth as [[Bunratty]], but it is likely she was born at Clonderalaw. The family tradition states her place of birth as Urlan More, but it is more likely that she was fostered there. She married Daniel Neylon in 1634, the marriage having been arranged. She was widowed in 1639,<ref name=\"Murphy\" /> with three young sons, William, Daniel and Michael.<ref name=\"Clare Library\" /> She managed the large Neylon estate until her son William came of age.<ref name=\"Murphy\" />\n\nThe necklace in one of O'Brien's portraits, dating the 1640s, is said to of came from the Spanish armada.{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n==Life at Leamaneh Castle==\nIt is known that within seven months of her first husband daniel Neylon's death she married her cousin and a Irish rebel Conor O'Brien of Leamaneh. They extended and fortified the O'Brien tower house at Leamaneh, creating Leamaneh castle. An inscription on the castle gate arch reads: \"This was built in the year of Our Lord 1648 by Conor O'Brien and Mary n\u00ed Mahon alias Brien wife to the said Conor\".The couple had eight children, with the eldest Sir Donough O'Brien, 1st Baronet Donough, was born in 1642. The other known children were Teige, Turlough, Murrough, Honora, and Mary, with two other daughters who are believed to have died during the plague which struck the area during the siege of Limerick.   Maire rua and her husband were brave Irish rebels and used led there army raiding and killing English settlers. But in 1651 conor fought against Edmund Ludlow and the Cromwellian army at the pass of Inchicronan while Maire rua barricaded and protected the castle. Conor was injured and It is told that when his body was returned to Leamaneh, Maire rua O'Brien leaned out of a window and declared that \"We want no dead men here\", and when the Irish soliders convinced her they were not Cromwellian soliders trying to ambush her and that conor was not dead yet. She let them in and nursed her wounded husband till he died that night to her devastation\n. \nVery soon after her husband's death, devastated maire rua knew that she and her children would be hung and her lands fortifed so she rode by horse to limreck city to the camp of general Henry Ireton dressed in all her finery proclaiming that she was willing to marry any of the officers.she married a Cromwellian officer John cooper and secured her property and castle from seizure. and was living with him in Limerick for a while after there marriage before returning to Leamaneh. They are believed to have had a son, Harry, and possibly a daughter. But Maire did not leave her Irish rebel ways and while her Cromwellian husband was often gone getting wealthy on land deals, she Often had secret affairs with the many Cromwellian soliders stationed on and off at the castle garrison and murdered them in various cruel ways that looked like accidents. She also used hang her English servants the woman by the hair and male servants by the neck from the castle corbels if they made one mistake. Maire rua O'Brien is alleged to have killed her Cromwellian husband with a kick in the stomach while shaving and cut his throat ,<ref name=\"Murphy\" /> but other sources show they remained married for a number of years but most likely lived apart.<ref name=\"Clare Library\" /> \u2264 though it is unknown how he died she may of killed him to claim his money. After the restoration, maire was indicted for the murder of a local English landlord . She received a royal pardon in 1662, but was still put on trial, which continued for years.<ref name=\"Murphy\" /> Her son, Donough, moved the O'Brien family seat to [[Dromoland Castle]] where she lived the final years of her life.<ref name=\"Clare Library\" /> < privates papers of lord of inchiquin. National library of Ireland   < \"the strangers gaze travels in co Clare 1534-1950\\>\n\n==Death and subsequent legends==\nO'Brien is reported to have died an extraordinary death, with one legend stating <s>Toonagh</s> Wood <s>by</s> <s>her</s> <s>hair</s>, and that she still haunts that wood, a second recounts how she was sealed into a hollow tree in Carnelly. It is more likely that she died from the poor health she was suffering when she signed a will on 7 June 1686. She requests to be buried in the abbey of Ennis, and though there is no marker, it is probable she is buried beside her husband, Conor O'Brien.<ref name=\"Murphy\" /> Others contend that she is buried at Coad church in Kilnaboy parish with two of her daughters.<ref name=\"Clare Library\" /> There are two known portraits of O'Brien, one held by the O'Brien family, and the second in Dromoland Castle Hotel.<ref name=\"Murphy\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:M\u00e1ire Rua}}\n[[Category:1610s births]]\n[[Category:1686 deaths]]\n[[Category:17th-century Irish people]]\n[[Category:Irish nobility]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| honorific_prefix   = \n| name               = M\u00e1ire Rua O'Brien\n| honorific_suffix   = \n| image              = M\u00e1ire Rua O'Brien.jpg\n| image_size         = \n| alt                = \n| caption            = \n| native_name        = \n| native_name_lang   = \n| birth_name         = M\u00e1ire Rua MacMahon\n| birth_date         = 1615/1616\n| birth_place        = [[Clonderalaw]], County Clare, Ireland\n| death_date         = 1686 (aged 70/71)\n| death_place        = \n| resting_place      = \n| residence          = \n| nationality        = Irish\n| citizenship        = \n| known_for          = \n| notable_works      = \n| parents            = \n| relatives          = \n| signature          = \n}}\n\n'''M\u00e1ire Rua O'Brien''' (1615/1616 \u2013 1686) was an Irish aristocrat, and notorious figure in Irish legend for her violent and murderous actions. <ref name=Murphy>{{cite book|last1=Murphy|first1=Maureen|editor1-last=McGuire|editor1-first=James|editor2-last=Quinn|editor2-first=James|title=[[Dictionary of Irish Biography]]|date=2009|publisher=Cambridge University Press|location=Cambridge|chapter=O'Brien, M\u00e1ire (\u2018M\u00e1ire Rua\u2019)}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nM\u00e1ire Rua O'Brien was born in 1615 or 1616.<ref name=\"Clare Library\">{{cite web |title=Clare People: Maire Rua |url=http://www.clarelibrary.ie/eolas/coclare/people/ruadh.htm |website=www.clarelibrary.ie |accessdate=2 April 2020}}</ref> She was known as M\u00e1ire Rua or Red Mary due to her red hair.<ref name=\"Aesthete\">{{cite web |title=The Legacy of M\u00e1ire R\u00faa |url=https://theirishaesthete.com/2016/10/19/the-legacy-of-maire-rua/ |website=The Irish Aesthete |accessdate=2 April 2020 |date=19 October 2016}}</ref> She was the daughter of lord of East Corcabaskin or [[Clonderalaw]], Sir Torlach Rua MacMahon and the youngest daughter of [[Connor O'Brien, 3rd Earl of Thomond]], Mary. Some sources have her place of birth as [[Bunratty]], but it is likely she was born at Clonderalaw. The family tradition states her place of birth as Urlan More, but it is more likely that she was fostered there. She married Daniel Neylon in 1634, the marriage having been arranged. She was widowed in 1639,<ref name=\"Murphy\" /> with three young sons, William, Daniel and Michael.<ref name=\"Clare Library\" /> She managed the large Neylon estate until her son William came of age.<ref name=\"Murphy\" />\n\nThe necklace in one of O'Brien's portraits, dating the 1640s, is said to of came from the Spanish armada.{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n==Life at Leamaneh Castle==\nThe legends of O'Brien describe her as having between 12 and 25 husbands, all of whom she killed. It is known that within seven months of Neylon's death, she married Conor O'Brien of Leamaneh. They extended the O'Brien tower house at Leamaneh, creating [[Leamaneh Castle]]. An inscription on the castle reads: \"This was built in the year of Our Lord 1648 by Conor O'Brien and Mary n\u00ed Mahon alias Brien wife to the said Conor\". The couple had eight children, with the eldest Sir [[Sir Donough O'Brien, 1st Baronet|Donough]], was born in 1642.<ref name=\"Murphy\" /> The other known children were Teige, Turlough, Murrough, Honora, and Mary, with two other daughters who are believed to have died during the plague which struck the area during the siege of Limerick.<ref name=\"Clare Library\" /> It is at Leamaneh Castle that O'Brien's violence and murders are associated, where it is alleged she would hang her servants who displeased her with from the corbels of the castle. It is also said that she victimised passers-by and trespassers. The folklorist [[M\u00e1ire MacNeill]] found parallels between some of the stories told about O'Brien, such as challenging suitors to ride a wide stallion, to those of traditional Irish sovereign-goddess myths.<ref name=\"Murphy\" />\n\nDuring the Irish wars from [[Confederate Ireland|1641 to 1652]], her husband led and financed one of the five militia companies of Clare which raided towers houses of Dutch and English settlers, with O'Brien riding with him during some raids. In the proceeding depositions about the siege of Barntick castle, O'Brien is charged with the murder of a servant. Conor O'Brien was commissioned colonel of horse in 1650 to the army of [[Charles II of England|Charles II]], dying in 1651 from wounds he received fighting against [[Edmund Ludlow]] at the pass of Inchecrogan. It is told that when his body was returned to Leamaneh, O'Brien leaned out of a window and declared that \"We want no dead men here\", and when they convinced her they were not Cromwellian soliders trying to ambush her and that he was not dead. She let them in and nursed her husband till he died that night. and that she later drove to the Limerick camp of [[Henry Ireton]] dressed in blue silk and lace proclaiming that she was willing to marry any of the officers.<ref name=\"Murphy\" /> Other accounts state that her husband was still alive when he was brought to the castle, and that she nursed him on his death bed. It is suggested that she may have wanted to marry a Cromwellian officer in an effort of secure her property and land from seizure.<ref name=\"Clare Library\" />\n\nVery soon after her husband's death, she petitioned Charles I's lord deputy in Ireland, [[Ulick Burke, 1st Marquess of Clanricarde|Ulick Burke]], to become the custodian of the O'Brien estate. She was able to secure the land for her children, she could not retain Leamaneh Castle, which fell to the Cromwellian army and was turned into a garrison. In 1653, she is recorded as the wife of a former parliamentary officer, Cornet John Cooper and was living with him in Limerick for a while after there marriage before returning to Leamaneh. They are believed to have had a son, Harry, and possibly a daughter.<ref name=\"Clare Library\" /> It is Cooper that Maire rua O'Brien is alleged to have killed with a kick in the stomach ,<ref name=\"Murphy\" /> but other sources show they remained married for a number of years but most likely lived apart.<ref name=\"Clare Library\" />  After the restoration, O'Brien was indicted for the murder of a local English landlord . She received a royal pardon in 1662, but was still put on trial, which continued for years.<ref name=\"Murphy\" /> Her son, Donough, moved the O'Brien family seat to [[Dromoland Castle]] where she lived the final years of her life.<ref name=\"Clare Library\" />\n\n==Death and subsequent legends==\nO'Brien is reported to have died an extraordinary death, with one legend stating <s>Toonagh</s> Wood <s>by</s> <s>her</s> <s>hair</s>, and that she still haunts that wood, a second recounts how she was sealed into a hollow tree in Carnelly. It is more likely that she died from the poor health she was suffering when she signed a will on 7 June 1686. She requests to be buried in the abbey of Ennis, and though there is no marker, it is probable she is buried beside her husband, Conor O'Brien.<ref name=\"Murphy\" /> Others contend that she is buried at Coad church in Kilnaboy parish with two of her daughters.<ref name=\"Clare Library\" /> There are two known portraits of O'Brien, one held by the O'Brien family, and the second in Dromoland Castle Hotel.<ref name=\"Murphy\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:M\u00e1ire Rua}}\n[[Category:1610s births]]\n[[Category:1686 deaths]]\n[[Category:17th-century Irish people]]\n[[Category:Irish nobility]]\n", "name_user": "Cathalohagan25", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eLife at Leamaneh Castle)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/M%C3%A1ire_Rua_O%27Brien"}
{"title_page": "Lugazi", "text_new": "{{about|the Ugandan town|the Latvian settlement|Luga\u017ei}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n<!--See the Table at Infobox Settlement for all fields and descriptions of usage-->\n<!-- Basic info  ---------------->\n|official_name          = Lugazi\n|other_name             = Kawolo\n|native_name            =  <!-- for cities whose native name is not in English -->\n|nickname               = \n|settlement_type        = <!--For Town or Village (Leave blank for the default City)-->\n|motto                  =\n<!-- images and maps  ----------->\n|image_skyline          = \n|imagesize              = \n|image_caption          = \n|image_flag             = \n|flag_size              =\n|image_seal             = \n|seal_size              =\n|image_shield           = \n|shield_size            =\n|image_blank_emblem     =\n|blank_emblem_type      =\n|blank_emblem_size      =\n|image_map              = \n|mapsize                = \n|map_caption            = \n|image_map1             = \n|mapsize1               = \n|map_caption1           = \n|image_dot_map          =\n|dot_mapsize            =\n|dot_map_caption        =\n|dot_x =  |dot_y =\n|pushpin_map            = Uganda<!-- the name of a location map as per http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Template:Location_map -->\n|pushpin_label_position = bottom\n|pushpin_map_caption    = Location in Uganda\n<!-- Location ------------------>\n|subdivision_type       = Country\n|subdivision_name       = [[Image:Flag of Uganda.svg|25px]] [[Uganda]]\n|subdivision_type1      = [[Regions of Uganda|Region]]\n|subdivision_name1      = [[Central Region, Uganda|Central Region of Uganda]]\n|subdivision_type2      = [[Districts of Uganda|District]]\n|subdivision_name2      = [[Buikwe District]]\n|subdivision_type3      = \n|subdivision_name3      = \n|subdivision_type4      = \n|subdivision_name4      =\n<!-- Politics ----------------->\n|government_footnotes   =\n|government_type        =\n|leader_title           = Mayor\n|leader_name            = Tumwesigye Deo Mbabazi \n<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.newvision.co.ug/D/8/19/642635 | date=3 August 2008 | title=Lugazi Residents Back Land Bill | accessdate=21 January 2015 | last=Moses Odongo | first=and Sulaiman Matovu | newspaper=[[New Vision]] (Kampala) | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150122001125/http://www.newvision.co.ug/D/8/19/642635 | archivedate=22 January 2015 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title=Uganda: Who Owns Lugazi Town? | newspaper=[[The Observer (Uganda)]] via [[AllAfrica.com]] | accessdate=21 January 2015 | first=Jackie | url=http://allafrica.com/stories/201310300069.html | date=29 October 2013 | last=Nalubwama}}</ref>\n|leader_title1          =  <!-- for places with, say, both a mayor and a city manager -->\n|leader_name1           =\n|leader_title2          =\n|leader_name2           =\n|leader_title3          =\n|leader_name3           =\n|leader_title4          =\n|leader_name4           =\n|established_title      =  <!-- Settled -->\n|established_date       = \n|established_title2     =  <!-- Incorporated (town) -->\n|established_date2      = \n|established_title3     =  <!-- Incorporated (city) -->\n|established_date3      =\n<!-- Area    --------------------->\n|area_magnitude         = \n|unit_pref                =\n|area_footnotes           =\n|area_total_km2           = <!-- ALL fields dealing with a measurements are subject to automatic unit conversion-->\n|area_land_km2            = <!--See table @ Template:Infobox Settlement for details on automatic unit conversion-->\n|area_water_km2           =\n|area_total_sq_mi         =\n|area_land_sq_mi          =\n|area_water_sq_mi         =\n|area_water_percent       =\n|area_urban_km2           =\n|area_urban_sq_mi         =\n|area_metro_km2           =\n|area_metro_sq_mi         =\n|area_blank1_title        =\n|area_blank1_km2          =\n|area_blank1_sq_mi        =\n<!-- Population   ----------------------->\n|population_as_of               = 2014 Census\n|population_footnotes           =<ref name=\"LGZI\"/>\n|population_note                =\n|population_total               = 114163\n|population_density_km2         =\n|population_density_sq_mi       =\n|population_metro               =\n|population_density_metro_km2   =\n|population_density_metro_sq_mi =\n|population_urban               =\n|population_density_urban_km2   =\n|population_density_urban_sq_mi =\n|population_blank1_title        =Ethnicities\n|population_blank1              =\n|population_blank2_title        =Religions\n|population_blank2              =\n|population_density_blank1_km2 =   \n|population_density_blank1_sq_mi =\n<!-- General information  --------------->\n|timezone               = \n|utc_offset             = \n|timezone_DST           = \n|utc_offset_DST         = \n|coordinates            = {{coord|00|22|08|N|32|56|25|E|region:UG|display=inline}}\n|elevation_footnotes    =  <!--for references: use <ref> tags-->\n|elevation_m            =1204 \n|elevation_ft           =\n<!-- Area/postal codes & others -------->\n|postal_code_type       =  <!-- enter ZIP code, Postcode, Post code, Postal code... -->\n|postal_code            =\n|area_code              =\n|blank_name             =\n|blank_info             =\n|blank1_name            =\n|blank1_info            =\n|website                = \n|footnotes              = \n}}\n\n'''Lugazi''' is a town in the [[Buikwe District]] of the [[Central Region, Uganda|Central Region]] of [[Uganda]]. The town is also called \"Kawolo\", and the two names are interchangeably used by the local inhabitants.{{fact|date=July 2015}}\n\n==Location==\nThe town is on the [[Kampala-Jinja Highway]], approximately {{convert|45|km|mi}} by road, east of [[Kampala]], Uganda's capital and largest city.<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=21 January 2015|date=| url=http://distancecalculator.globefeed.com/Uganda_Distance_Result.asp?fromplace=Kampala%2C%20Central%20Region%2C%20Uganda&toplace=Lugazi%2C%20Central%20Region%2C%20Uganda%2C&dt1=ChIJm7N0nQ-8fRcR7G9r2T2QOEU&dt2=ChIJpa0KsnPQfRcRHr5ABSLcsaw|title=Road Distance Between Kampala And Lugazi With Interactive Map| publisher=Globefeed.com}}</ref> Its is approximately {{convert|23|km|mi}}, by road, east of [[Mukono]], the nearest large town, also on the highway between Kampala and [[Jinja, Uganda|Jinja]].<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=21 January 2015| url=http://distancecalculator.globefeed.com/Uganda_Distance_Result.asp?fromplace=Mukono%2C%20Central%20Region%2C%20Uganda&toplace=Lugazi%2C%20Central%20Region%2C%20Uganda%2C&dt1=ChIJpbAJFLfHfRcRcMWeVCv42t0&dt2=ChIJpa0KsnPQfRcRHr5ABSLcsaw|\ntitle=Map Showing Mukono And Lugazi With Interactive Route Marker|\npublisher=Globefeed.com}}</ref> The average elevation of the Lugazi is about {{convert|1204|m|ft}}.{{fact|date=July 2015}} The coordinates of Lugazi are 0\u00b022'08.0\"N, 32\u00b056'25.0\"E (Latitude:0.368889; Longitude:32.940278).<ref>{{google maps | accessdate=14 July 2015 | title=Location of Lugazi At Google Maps | url=https://www.google.com/maps/place/0%C2%B022'08.0%22N+32%C2%B056'25.0%22E/@0.36922,32.9411974,17z/data=!4m2!3m1!1s0x0:0x0}}</ref>\n\n==Points of interest==\nThe following points of interest lie within the town or close to its boundaries:\n[[File:Uganda 2012 a010.jpg|thumb|Cathedral of Our Lady Queen of Peace]]\n* offices of Lugazi Town Council\n* headquarters of the [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Lugazi]]\n* Lugazi central market\n* headquarters of the [[Mehta Group]] in Uganda\n* [[University of Military Science and Technology]], which is owned and administered by the [[Uganda People's Defence Force]]\n* [[Mount Saint Mary's College Namagunga]], located {{convert|5.5|km|mi}}, by road, west of downtown Lugazi in [[Mukono District]]\n* Kawolo Hospital, a 200-bed public hospital administered by the [[Uganda Ministry of Health]]\n* Lugazi Golf Course, which is located on the grounds of SCUL\n* branch of the [[National Social Security Fund (Uganda)]]\n* [[Kampala-Jinja Highway]], passing through the center of town in an east/west configuration\n\n==Population==\nThe 2002 national census estimated the population of Lugazi at 27,979. In 2010, the Uganda Bureau of Statistics (UBOS) estimated the population at 34,500. In 2011, UBOS estimated the population at 35,500.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ubos.org/onlinefiles/uploads/ubos/pdf%20documents/TP52010.pdf |format=PDF |title=Estimated Population of Lugazi In 2002, 2010 & 2011 |date=2011 |accessdate=21 January 2015 |publisher=[[Uganda Bureau of Statistics]] (UBOS) |last=UBOS |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140707231502/http://www.ubos.org/onlinefiles/uploads/ubos/pdf%20documents/TP52010.pdf |archivedate=7 July 2014 }}</ref> In 2014, the national census put the population at 114,163.<ref name=\"LGZI\">\"{{cite web | url=http://citypopulation.de/Uganda-Cities.html | title=The Population of The Regions of the Republic of Uganda And All Cities And Towns of More Than 15,000 Inhabitants | date=27 August 2014 | accessdate=26 February 2015 | last=UBOS | publisher=Citypopulation.de Quoting [[Uganda Bureau of Statistics]] (UBOS)}}</ref>\n\n==Sports==\nIn 2012, a Little League baseball team from Lugazi qualified for the [[2012 Little League World Series]] in [[Williamsport, Pennsylvania]]. This was the second ever team from Uganda to qualify and the first to make the trip to the USA.<ref>{{cite web |\nlast=Communications Division | title=Lugazi Little League of Uganda Wins Regional Title, to be First African Team In Little League Baseball World Series | publisher=Little League Online | url=http://www.littleleague.org/Page58970.aspx | accessdate=21 January 2015 | date=16 July 2012}}</ref> The team that qualified in [[2011 Little League World Series|2011]] were denied visas by the State Department, therefore having to concede the [[Little League World Series (Middle East-Africa Region)|MEA]] region title to [[Dhahran|Dhahran, Saudi Arabia]].\n\nLugazi is also the home of the [[Uganda Revenue Authority SC]], a member of the Uganda Premier Soccer League.\n\n==See also==\n\n*[[Roman Catholic Diocese of Lugazi]]\n*[[List of cities and towns in Uganda]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Buikwe District}}\n{{coord|00|23|00|N|32|55|27|E|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Populated places in Uganda]]\n[[Category:Cities in the Great Rift Valley]]\n[[Category:Buikwe District]]\n[[Category:Central Region, Uganda]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|the Ugandan town|the Latvian settlement|Luga\u017ei}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n<!--See the Table at Infobox Settlement for all fields and descriptions of usage-->\n<!-- Basic info  ---------------->\n|official_name          = Lugazi\n|other_name             = Kawolo\n|native_name            =  <!-- for cities whose native name is not in English -->\n|nickname               = \n|settlement_type        = <!--For Town or Village (Leave blank for the default City)-->\n|motto                  =\n<!-- images and maps  ----------->\n|image_skyline          = \n|imagesize              = \n|image_caption          = \n|image_flag             = \n|flag_size              =\n|image_seal             = \n|seal_size              =\n|image_shield           = \n|shield_size            =\n|image_blank_emblem     =\n|blank_emblem_type      =\n|blank_emblem_size      =\n|image_map              = \n|mapsize                = \n|map_caption            = \n|image_map1             = \n|mapsize1               = \n|map_caption1           = \n|image_dot_map          =\n|dot_mapsize            =\n|dot_map_caption        =\n|dot_x =  |dot_y =\n|pushpin_map            = Uganda<!-- the name of a location map as per http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Template:Location_map -->\n|pushpin_label_position = bottom\n|pushpin_map_caption    = Location in Uganda\n<!-- Location ------------------>\n|subdivision_type       = Country\n|subdivision_name       = [[Image:Flag of Uganda.svg|25px]] [[Uganda]]\n|subdivision_type1      = [[Regions of Uganda|Region]]\n|subdivisio